<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Fixed phones ride the airwaves: Andrew Adonis on technology
that could provide cheap networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An idea as revolutionary as the mobile phone was a decade ago could provide
telecommunications networks which replace miles of costly copper wire with
radio waves.
The technology is being developed in the UK for launch in early 1995 by
Ionica, based in Cambridge.
Mr Nigel Playford, Ionica's founder and managing director, says the wireless
system, which will link exchanges with fixed phones in homes and businesses
using signals from a network of base stations, will slash the cost of
building and operating local phone networks. This will boost competition in
a sector which has been a virtual BT monopoly.
Ionica secured a UK licence in February, but has spent nearly three years on
research and development. 'Markets create services,' says Mr Playford, an
electronics engineer turned entrepreneur.
The market was created by the government's abolition of the BT/Mercury
duopoly in 1991, and Mr Playford and two others launched the company that
year. It now has about 150 employees, including designers from Northern
Telecom, the project's main contractor.
The Ionica service for the UK will be geared to the existing market of more
than 20m fixed phone subscribers. A receiving antenna, like a television
aerial, will be attached to the roof of each subscribing home or business.
Ionica is confident it can provide a service without the fluctuations in
signal quality experienced with mobile receivers.
'With copper-wire networks, capital investment has to be up front. With us,
most of it follows the customer,' Mr Playford said. Only the base stations -
each of which would cost about Pounds 10,000 and could serve about 1,000
customers - are 'up front'.
The rest of the investment - the antenna and internal wiring - is made only
after the customer has signed up. While cable TV companies spend about
Pounds 5bn building networks in conurbations, Ionica plans to cover half the
country for about Pounds 100m by 1997.
The company plans to offer a national service, aiming for a foothold in the
small-business and residential market. It intends to guarantee sizeable
savings on BT prices and will offer features such as three-way calling,
voice messaging, and extra lines at low cost - each antenna link will be
able to carry up to eight lines.
For larger businesses, the fact that radio waves cannot cope with heavy data
transfer will reduce Ionica's appeal.
By creating an alternative 'local loop', Ionica is targeting the least
competitive part of BT's market. Even when the cable companies have
completed their networks, they will cover less than half of the UK.
Ionica's radio waves will connect to BT's principal exchanges via parallel
Ionica exchanges. It will send the trunk portion of calls over the BT
network, or that of one of its long-distance competitors.
In doing so, it is able to exploit the most competitive part of the UK
telecoms market, the long distance networks.
With at least three nationwide long-distance operators in the market by 1995
 -BT, Mercury and Energis, a subsidiary of National Grid - and BT making
hefty margins on its trunk business, Ionica expects to be offered attractive
deals.
Backers include Northern Electric, Yorkshire Electricity and Telecom
Finland. About Pounds 30m of the Pounds 100m needed has already been raised.
But launching the service will be far from simple. Capital has to be raised
to fund an unfamiliar venture. Base station sites have to be found.
Does the technology work? There is some scepticism in the telecommunications
world. Trials in East Anglia next year will show whether Ionica's radio
quality is up to that offered by copper and fibre. It also has to ensure
uninterrupted service quality in hilly areas.
Meanwhile, imitation is flattery: Mercury, the main UK competitor to BT,
recently announced its intention to test wireless technology, with a view to
possible introduction not long after Ionica. Millicom, a US company, is also
planning a radio-based service.
The system has strong attractions for developing countries with inadequate
fixed networks. The Mexican government recently received an application to
build a second national telecommunications network using the technology
developed by Ionica.
The request for a Mexican licence by Pulsar, the Mexican conglomerate
founded by multi-billionaire Mr Alfonso Romo Garza, could be a milestone.
</TEXT>
<XX>
