<PROFILE>_AN-DLGD5ACEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931207
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Backing for review of child support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The controversial Child Support Agency came under renewed fire from MPs
yesterday, following publication of a Commons social security committee
report broadly endorsing the agency's role in collecting maintenance
payments from absent parents.
At question time in the Commons Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary,
welcomed the report and promised to examine recommendations aimed at easing
the burden of payments on absentee fathers.
Tory backbenchers joined opposition MPs in protesting that the agency was
not concentrating on tracing absent parents who failed to pay maintenance
for their children.
The committee's report called for changes in the formula for calculating
maintenance payments to reduce the burden on absent fathers. It recommended
that big increases in maintenance be phased in over up to two years. It
endorsed the principles behind the agency, however, in spite of widespread
concern about the way maintenance is calculated.
Mr Lilley said reaction to the agency came from 'men who were reluctant to
pay in full the costs of maintaining their children'. He added: 'It is
inevitable there should be some resistance to paying in full the costs of
maintaining children .'
Mr Bill Cash, Conservative MP for Stafford, said Tory backbenchers were
'delighted' that the workings of the agency were to be reviewed.
</TEXT>
