<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Budget worries slow consumer credit rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer borrowing slackened ahead of the Budget due to concerns about large
tax increases, government figures suggested yesterday.
Net lending to consumers by finance houses and building societies and on
credit cards in the Visa and Mastercard systems came to Pounds 311m in
October, compared with Pounds 489m in September.
The figures provide a warning that the recent strong growth in consumer
activity could run out of steam should people start to worry about the
effects on disposable income of the Pounds 8.1bn tax increases coming into
force in April.
Before last week's Budget many people were concerned that the government
might impose still greater tax increases than the Pounds 1.4bn announced in
addition to the Pounds 6.7bn of tax increases already in the pipeline for
April.
Between August and October lending was Pounds 1.025bn, up from Pounds 535m
in the previous three months and the highest three-month figure for nearly
three years.
The Treasury said that, even allowing for the sharp fall between September
and October in the seasonally adjusted lending figure, the October total was
the second highest since April 1991.
Although the Central Statistical Office lending figures do not include
mortgages, the figures are considered a reliable guide to consumer
behaviour.
Net lending by finance houses increased slightly from Pounds 336m in
September to Pounds 349m the following month, with much of this cash going
on durable goods such as cars, carpets and cookers. A net Pounds 31m was
repaid on credit card loans in October, however, indicating a move away from
using cards to finance new spending. The repayment followed a net increase
in card loans of Pounds 106m in September.
October also saw a net repayment on loans taken out through building
societies. Consumers paid back Pounds 7m in October, after boosting
borrowing by Pounds 47m in the previous month.
The amount of new credit to consumers - which does not take repayments into
account - came to Pounds 4.39bn in October, down from a record Pounds
4.848bn in September.
</TEXT>
