<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Backing for review of child support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The controversial Child Support Agency came under renewed fire from MPs
yesterday, following publication of a Commons social security committee
report broadly endorsing the agency's role in collecting maintenance
payments from absent parents.
At question time in the Commons Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary,
welcomed the report and promised to examine recommendations aimed at easing
the burden of payments on absentee fathers.
Tory backbenchers joined opposition MPs in protesting that the agency was
not concentrating on tracing absent parents who failed to pay maintenance
for their children.
The committee's report called for changes in the formula for calculating
maintenance payments to reduce the burden on absent fathers. It recommended
that big increases in maintenance be phased in over up to two years.
It endorsed the principles behind the agency, however, in spite of
widespread concern about the way maintenance is calculated.
Mr Lilley said reaction to the agency came from 'men who were reluctant to
pay in full the costs of maintaining their children'.
He added: 'It is inevitable there should be some resistance to paying in
full the costs of maintaining children if people have not been doing so up
to now.'
Mr Bill Cash, Conservative MP for Stafford, said Tory backbenchers were
'delighted' that the workings of the agency were to be reviewed. 'There are
a number of very serious problems which I have come across in my
constituency.'
Mr Adam Ingram, Labour MP for East Kilbride, said there was 'very real
anger' at the way government policy had been enforced.
Mr Lilley replied that in 96 per cent of cases dealt with by the agency the
mothers and children had been on benefit while the fathers usually had a
reasonable income.
Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the Commons committee, said it was
'imperative' that the government accepted in full the report's
recommendations. 'Failure to do so, or to cherry pick over the
recommendations, will lead to a breaking up of political support for this
reform.'
</TEXT>
