<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Budget debate rules attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A cross-party committee of MPs yesterday accused the government of stifling
debate on the first unified Budget, delivered last week by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor.
In a sharply critical report, the procedure committee says the government
has rejected proposals for radical changes in the parliamentary arrangements
for the Budget.
The committee, chaired by Sir Peter Emery, Conservative MP for Honiton, says
that the government has 'failed in the objective it set itself of enabling
'a more informed and focused debate'.'
The report shows that the government rejected a series of proposals by the
committee. They included:
Splitting the finance bill to allow detailed tax changes to be presented in
a separate taxes management bill.
Setting up a standing committee of MPs to consider the details of technical
changes in taxation regulations.
Delaying the start of the Budget debate for two days to allow MPs to digest
the contents of the chancellor's speech.
Allowing minority parties and individual MPs to table amendments to the
chancellor's spending and taxation plans, in addition to the traditional
opposition amendment.
In its response to the committee the government said that its proposals
amounted to 'a radical change' in procedures which would create 'confusion'.
The committee, which has a Conservative majority, says an amendment to the
ruleswould allow MPs to express an opinion on the Budget strategy without
affecting the passage of the finance bill.
The committee says: 'The range of economic policy options available at any
one time must justify a vote on more than just one amendment. To refuse this
is stifling the expression of views of the minority parties or of the
strength of feeling of a minority within the government party.'
</TEXT>
