<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Jump in loyalist paramilitary recruitment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Recruitment to loyalist paramilitary groups has accelerated amid revelations
about communication between the British government and Sinn Fein, and
loyalist suspicion of the London-Dublin peace initiative, security sources
believe.
One assessment by the security forces puts the armed active strength of the
Ulster Volunteer Force and the Ulster Freedom Fighters at about 200  -
compared with 500 to 600 IRA 'volunteers'.
The UVF and UFF are thought to be recruiting young, mostly unemployed
Protestants, and attempting to raise funds from businesses.
Mr Jim Rodgers, a Belfast Ulster Unionist party councillor who has strong
contacts with the loyalist community, described official estimates of
loyalist military strength as 'rubbish' and said he had information
suggesting that the strength of support for the UVF and UFF was running into
thousands.
He said: 'The rate of recruitment at the moment is staggering. People are
coming to realise that the only language the British government understands
is violence and that violence is going to have to be used to prevent the
majority being pushed into a united Ireland against their wishes.'
Unionist politicians have frequently exaggerated the threat of a loyalist
backlash. But fears about a backlash are increasing in the army. One
security source expressed concern that loyalists trained in the army might
take their expertise to the paramilitaries.
Of the 79 terrorist killings in Northern Ireland this year 33 are accounted
for by the IRA and 46 by loyalists.
The UVF and UFF have concentrated on killings planned at short notice. They
have so far failed to obtain Semtex or commercial explosives to carry out a
large operation.
Thousands of Protestants would be forced to leave Ulster within a decade of
unity between north and south, Mr John Taylor, UUP MP for Strangford, said
last night.
</TEXT>
