<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Shake-up on road costings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government may in future award road-building contracts to companies
which guarantee to keep down future maintenance costs rather than to those
which submit the lowest bid.
The Department of Transport yesterday announced the first contract to be
awarded under a new 'whole-life costing scheme' which takes expected
maintenance costs and traffic delays into account.
A Pounds 34m contract for the construction of the 3 1/2 -mile Brockworth
bypass near Gloucester went to Wimpey Construction.
The department has spent the past two years devising a computer model to
assess the total costs of different road surfaces. Contractors are given the
figures for future costs to help them frame bids.
Wimpey said it had submitted three bids for the Brockworth contract
involving different road surfaces. This was normal practice, it said.
Tarmac roads need strengthening halfway through their 40-year lives while
concrete roads do not, but this does not mean concrete will automatically be
cheaper.
Whole-life costing did not make a great deal of difference to the Brockworth
bypass contract because Wimpey was the lowest bidder anyway, the Department
of Transport said.
Mr Robert Key, roads minister, said: 'The aim of whole life costing is to
tell us if it is worth providing roads that give longer life and need less
maintenance.'
</TEXT>
