<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Education bill faces rebellion by Tory peers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Opposition peers expect the government to have difficulty getting its new
education bill through parliament in its current form because of a growing
rebellion by Tory peers.
The bill, which would reform the organisation of teacher training and end
compulsory membership of student unions, will be debated by parliament for
the first time today, when it receives its second reading in the upper
chamber.
An ominous sign for the government yesterday was that more than 30 peers had
applied to speak in the second reading debate, about three times the usual
number for such an event.
Baroness David, who speaks for the opposition on education, said that she
expected most of the speeches to be against the bill, and that there would
be a lot of pressure to amend it during and after its committee stage next
year.
Several Tory peers have already said that they will be speaking against the
legislation while a Labour whip yesterday promised that the bill's passage
through the chamber would turn into a 'marathon' for the government.
Department for Education officials are also admitting privately that the
legislation on student unions will be one of the most hotly contested
legislative issues in the new session. Vice-chancellors oppose it because,
they say, it is too prescriptive.
Under the bill the management of teacher training will be passed to an
agency responsible for its funding. It will be expected to move funds from
university departments to schools as part of 'school-based training'.
Professor Peter Mortimore, director of London University's Institute of
Education, said the move would be expensive, as it would create several
thousand providers of teacher-training, rather than the 90 at present.
He suggested that quality would also suffer, because of the added
difficulties of regulating so many schools, each of which would have a
teacher-training capacity.
He added that the government's ability to control the supply of teachers
would be damaged by the measure.
Sex must be placed in the context of morals and family values in school
lessons, Mr John Patten, the education secretary, said yesterday. He added:
'Sex education, like moral education, should begin in the home.' Parents
will be allowed to withdraw their children from any lesson including sex
education.
</TEXT>
