<HEADLINE>
FT  07 DEC 93 / Granada breaks ground with hostile LWT bid: Takeover offer
is rejected as shake-up of ITV intensifies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Granada launched the first hostile takeover bid in British commercial
television history that stands a chance of success with an offer for London
Weekend Television yesterday.
The bid, which values LWT at roughly Pounds 600m, was firmly rejected by Sir
Christopher Bland, its chairman.
It is further evidence of a fundamental realignment in the ITV system
following the government's decision last week to overhaul licensing rules.
If parliament approves the proposals, any ITV group will be allowed to own
two licences, however large the companies' revenues.
Previous bids for ITV companies were blocked by the old Independent
Broadcasting Authority.
If the Granada-LWT deal were to go through after last week's agreed takeover
by Carlton Communications of Central, the Midlands ITV company, the two
companies would control more than half ITV's Pounds 1.4bn-a-year advertising
revenues.
Mr Gerry Robinson, the chief executive of Granada, which broadcasts to the
north-west of England, offered six new Granada shares for every five LWT
shares, valuing LWT shares at 582p at yesterday's close, with a cash
alternative of 528p a share.
Unusually, the price offered by Granada, which also has interests in leisure
and business services, was at a discount of 0.5 per cent to the LWT share
price of 585p on December 3, the last dealing day before the bid's
announcement. Granada's shares closed 5p down at 485p and LWT's down 1p at
582p.
Mr Robinson emphasised that the offer represented a 54.8 per cent premium on
the LWT share price on June 28 when Granada first bought a stake in the
company, which broadcasts to the London region at the weekend. The holding
now stands at 17.5 per cent.
The deal was 'a full and fair' valuation for LWT, he said. It would create a
combined company accounting for about 22 per cent of total ITV advertising
revenue and reaching 16m viewers at least some time during the week.
The Granada offer was accompanied by an announcement of the group's results
for the year to October 2 showing a 53 per cent increase in pre-tax profits
to Pounds 176m on a turnover of Pounds 1.6bn. All divisions showed increases
in operating profits, with television up 30 per cent to Pounds 43m and a 56
per cent rise in earnings per share to 24.8p.
Granada, famous for programmes such as Coronation Street and more recent
drama hits such as Cracker and Prime Suspect, also promised cost savings
from rationalising the administration and support services of the new
company.
Granada's northern production centre in Manchester, Mr Robinson said, was
custom-built for drama series while LWT studios were ideal for light
entertainment production.
Mr Guy Lamming, media analyst at stockbrokers James Capel, believed Granada
would have to offer between 25p and 30p a share more for LWT. Sir
Christopher should then 'roll over' and accept the inevitable, he said.
It is far from clear if Sir Christopher and his management team, which
collectively own 10 per cent of the company, or shares worth Pounds 60m,
would give in at such a price.
LWT rejects suggestions from Granada that it is too small and marginalised
in the new world of commercial television by arguing that Granada, 'a
conglomerate with only 20 per cent of its operating profit derived from
television', had little to offer LWT shareholders.
LWT believes that, with its stakes in other television companies, it can
stand alone. Apart from 14 per cent of Yorkshire-Tyne Tees, the company has
a 20 per cent stake in the loss-making GMTV, the commercial breakfast
broadcaster, and 18 per cent in the profit-making Independent Television
News.
Observer, Page 17
Lex, Page 18
Granada steps up tempo in ITV game of musical chairs, Page 19
London stocks, Page 38
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Granada Group.
    LWT Holdings.
</CO>
