<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Tecs set for bigger industrial policy role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 82 training and enterprise councils in England and Wales are likely to
become the leading institutions in regional industrial policy after approval
for Kent Tec to take over the economic development activities of Kent County
Council.
The primary jobs of Tecs is to run the two main government training schemes
 -Youth Training and Employment Training for adults - but many of the
business executives on Tec boards are more interested in the mission to
raise the overall quality of business in their areas.
According to Mr Peter Ashby, a leading Tec consultant, the Kent takeover is
likely to promote a wave of similar moves, although in some areas Tecs might
merge with chambers of commerce.
The chairman of Kent Tec is Sir Alastair Morton, co-chairman of Eurotunnel
and a businessman with close links to government. He was recently made head
of the Treasury's private finance working group, set up to promote
private-sector investment in infrastructure projects.
The Kent merger is consequently almost certain to have official endorsement.
That means the government is taking the more permissive stance on
institutional links that Tec leaders have urged.
The Kent merger is also significant because it comes three weeks after the
government announced the establishment of Integrated Regional Offices,
bringing together at regional level such government departments as trade and
industry, transport, environment and employment.
IROs are responsible for urban regeneration budgets, and Tec-local authority
mergers will be in a strong position to bid for large parts of them. The
establishment of IROs is also a response to the Tec complaint that
government speaks in too many conflicting voices, especially at regional
level.
</TEXT>
