<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Sharper focus on careers advice in schools urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The lack of focus on careers education in the UK leaves many young British
people worse off than their continental counterparts for making a successful
transition to the world of work, a report published today says.
The report, from the National Institute of Economic and Social Research,
compares school vocational guidance in the UK, Germany, Switzerland and the
Netherlands.
Careers guidance on the Continent tends to starts earlier, is taught by
careers specialists in separate lessons devoted to the topic and is geared
to providing young people with detailed information on careers and ensuring
that courses taken at school are relevant. In Britain careers advice is not
part of the national curriculum and teachers are frequently untrained in
careers guidance.
The report comes when big changes are being made to the delivery of careers'
advice to young people. The government has taken it out of local authority
control and is seeking tenders from new providers, which may include local
authorities. The need for good quality advice has never been greater because
of the development of training credits, with young people able to seek out
prospective employers with whom they invest their credits in return for
training.
The report's recommendations include an earlier start to work experience,
the reinstatement of classes in vocational guidance, greater targeting of
relevant information through a detailed syllabus, more emphasis on
vocational guidance in teacher training and the greater involvement of
parents.
Smoothing the transition to skilled employment. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench St,
Smith Square, London SW1P 3HE. Pounds 3.
</TEXT>
