<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Discord on London orchestra cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Philharmonia has been chosen by Lord Justice Hoffmann to be the super
orchestra of London.
But his decision, given to the Arts Council music panel on Friday, has yet
to be made public and it seems unlikely the Hoffmann report will be accepted
without modification.
The council asked Lord Justice Hoffmann, a music lover, to conduct an
inquiry into three subsidised orchestras: the London Philharmonic, the Royal
Philharmonic and the Philharmonia, two of which would lose their subsidy.
The London Symphony Orchestra, resident at the Barbican, was excused the
competition.
There have been attempts for more than 20 years to reduce the number of
London-based orchestras receiving Arts Council subsidy, with the aim of
saving money and creating a world-class orchestra able to compete with the
best in Vienna and Berlin.
The contest raised a storm of controversy, not least because the odds seemed
stacked in favour of the LPO. It has just entered its second season of a
five-year residency as the orchestra of the South Bank Centre, with an
increased annual subsidy of Pounds 1.3m to allow for extra rehearsal time.
Lord Justice Hoffmann heard all three orchestras play and considered their
written proposals. His choice of the Philharmonia creates problems for the
South Bank and the Arts Council. Its music panel will have to decide whether
it agrees with the choice. Even if it does the full Arts Council, meeting
next week, can overturn the decision.
The LPO's position at the South Bank, with a series of concerts planned
years ahead, becomes impossible without a grant. If its concerts were
cancelled it might have a legal case against the Arts Council, which funds
the South Bank.
The RPO, which receives only Pounds 400,000 a year in subsidy, or 7 per cent
of its income, did not expect to be chosen but might now look more
favourably on an Arts Council proposal to make it the orchestra serving the
east of England.
The future of the Philharmonia, which receives Pounds 700,000 in annual
grant, seems secure. But it seems unlikely that the Arts Council will be
able to withdraw subsidy to the LPO suddenly from next April, just two years
after approving it.
The LPO has hit a bad patch, with a management shake-up in the summer and
continuing controversy over its principal conductor, Frans Welser-Most.
A compromise might be worked out. The problem is that the Arts Council had
its government grant for 1994-95 cut by 1.7 per cent in the Budget last
week. It does not have enough money to both increase support for the
Philharmonia and keep the other two orchestras afloat. It might defer a
decision until after its examination of the regional orchestras next year
with the BBC.
</TEXT>
<XX>
