FT  06 DEC 93 / BBC and Tussauds hold theme park talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC is looking at the possibility of building a multi-million-pound
theme park or exhibition centre in Britain which would feature some of its
best-known programmes.
The project is being examined with Pearson, owner of the Financial Times,
through its wholly-owned subsidiary Tussauds Group, which runs Alton Towers,
Chessington World of Adventures, Madame Tussaud's and the London
Planetarium.
Ms Juliete Simpkins of Tussauds Group said yesterday: 'I can confirm that we
are involved in a study with the BBC on building a theme park. But
discussions are at a very early stage. It would be a multi-million-pound
venture.'
Ideas being discussed for a park could cover theme restaurants, special
effects and replica sets of the BBC's successful shows.
These could include Dr Who, with an exhibition of fights between Cybermen
and Daleks, and East Enders, with a reproduction of Albert Square and the
Queen Vic public house.
The BBC said: 'We are talking to the Pearson group. But everything is at a
tentative stage. I cannot confirm what the park would cost.'
