FT  06 DEC 93 / Project to support sales to Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British Chambers of Commerce in Continental Europe has launched a
support service to help small and medium-sized UK companies win business on
the Continent.
The organisation, which operates in 11 European countries and has more than
6,000 members, has agreed to provide information and assistance to companies
which want to start selling in Continental markets.
Companies will be able to enlist the help of staff nominated in each local
chamber to analyse local market opportunities and to identify potential
customers. Mr John Major, the prime minister, has endorsed the move, which
will be supported by several government departments.
Mr Michael Ingham, president of the council of the British chambers, said:
'It is of the utmost importance, especially to small and medium-sized
companies, that there is a group of people throughout Europe ready to assist
them penetrate those markets.'
He said the level of support for British exporters in Europe had generally
compared unfavourably with that provided to their European competitors.
