FT  06 DEC 93 / BBC and Tussauds in theme park talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC is looking at the possibility of building a multi-million pound
theme park or exhibition centre in Britain which would feature some its
best-known programmes.
The project is being examined in conjunction with Pearson, owner of the
Financial Times, through its wholly-owned subsidiary Tussauds Group, which
runs Alton Towers, Chessington World of Adventures, Madame Tussaud's and the
London Planetarium.
Ms Juliete Simpkins of Tussauds Group said yesterday: 'I can confirm that we
are involved in a study with the BBC on building a theme park. But
discussions are at a very early stage. It would be a multi-million pound
venture. The feasibility study is meant to find out what a theme park would
cost.
Ideas being discussed for a park could cover theme restaurants, special
effects, and replica sets of the BBC's successful shows.
These could include Dr Who with an exhibition of fights between Cybermen and
Daleks, East Enders, with a reproduction of Albert Square and the Queen Vic
public house. Other sets suggested are Birds of a Feather, Casualty and
Noel's House Party.
The BBC said: 'We are interested in building a theme park. We are talking to
the Pearson group. But everything is at a tentative stage. I cannot confirm
what the park would cost or that Pearson would pay for it.'
Ms Simpkins said: 'The BBC theme park is one of a number of projects we are
looking at. Another possible scheme is in New York, where we are thinking
about a permanent show.'
The Tussauds Group runs the largest number of paid-for attractions in
Britain. These include Alton Towers in Staffordshire which last year
attracted 2.5m visitors and Madame Tussauds with 3.2m.
</TEXT>
