<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Whitehall officials forecast up to 6,000 job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 1,000 civil service jobs will go within a few months of
implementing the Budget plan to merge unemployment benefit and income
support into the jobseekers' allowance in 1996, say Whitehall officials.
They also say that up to 6,000 jobs will be lost over the following few
years.
It has long been accepted in Whitehall that the unemployed should be served
by one department rather than two as at present - the Department of
Employment for job-finding and the payment of unemployment benefit, and the
Department of Social Security for the payment of income support, which is
received by 70 per cent of the unemployed.
Officials say it is probable that the payment of the jobseekers' allowance
will be centralised in the Employment Service, a semi-autonomous agency in
the Department of Employment. The department's residual functions are likely
to be shared between the trade and industry and education departments.
One insider said: 'If the Conservatives win the next election (the
Department of) Employment is not likely to survive, but they will only be
able to close it if unemployment is falling,'
Currently about 32,000 people in the Employment Service and 12,000 in the
DSS are involved in the payment of unemployment-related benefits. If the
payment of JSA was to be concentrated on the DSS the benefit would lose its
labour-market focus. This has just been reinforced by the government's
insistence that JSA recipients must sign a jobseeker's agreement.
Claimants already agree a 'back to work plan' with an official at their
local Job Centre. But in the new agreement people will have to sign a
document and the onus will shift to claimants to prove that they are
actively seeking a job.
As well as reducing the duration of non-means-tested unemployment benefit
from 12 months to six months, under the JSA there will be no no higher rate
for people who are married or have dependants.
But in the harmonisation of the rules between the JSA and unemployment
benefit the partners of the unemployed will benefit, being allowed to work
24 hours a week rather than the previous 16 hours.
</TEXT>
