<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Export aid for companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Council of British Chambers of Commerce in Continental Europe has
launched a support service to help small and medium-sized UK companies win
business on the Continent.
The organisation, which operates in 11 European countries and has more than
6,000 members, has agreed to provide information and assistance to companies
which want to start selling in Continental markets. Companies will be able
to enlist the help of staff nominated in each chamber to analyse local
market opportunities and to identify potential customers.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, has endorsed the move, which will be
supported by several government departments.
Mr Michael Ingham, president of the council, said that the chambers had
represented an untapped resource for British exporters but they had now been
able to agree a joint plan of action to be adopted across Europe.
He said: 'It is of the utmost importance, especially to small and
medium-sized companies, that there is a group of people throughout Europe
ready to assist them.'
He said the level of support for British exporters in Europe had generally
compared unfavourably with that provided to their European competitors. The
British chambers had the right mix of business expertise and local market
knowledge to help redress the imbalance.
</TEXT>
