<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Logica leads battle project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A consortium of 17 European companies led by Logica, the British computing
services group, is developing a battlefield control system which could give
the UK and Europe a technological edge over the US in electronic warfare. It
may also have applications in civil systems, including the emergency
services and air traffic control.
The Grace consortium includes Matra Cap of France, Datamat of Italy, Indra
Sistemas of Spain and the Dutch National Aerospace Laboratory.
The contract, worth about Pounds 17m, is being funded under the European
Collaboration for the Long term in Defence (Euclid) programme. The defence
ministries of the participating seven countries have put up Pounds 2m each
and the companies are investing Pounds 3m.
Dr Derek Barnes of the UK Defence Research Agency, which is chairing the
Grace management group, said the project could provide a boost for European
industry.
The aim is to develop 'intelligent' computer software capable of handling,
processing and displaying large volumes of information of the kind generated
during a land or naval battle.
Dr Barnes said the project would ask fundamental questions, including
whether artificial intelligence was advanced enough to allow machines to
make strategic decisions. He added: 'The project could provide the basis for
a standard command and control workstation for European defence purposes.
The technology would also have applications in air traffic control,
ambulance despatch and oilfield management.
