<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Tokyo package dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa said early today that the
government was not considering an economic stimulus package, William Dawkins
and agencies report from Tokyo.
His announcement to the budget committee of the lower house of parliament
came as stocks suffered a sharp fall in early trading, with the Nikkei
average down more than 600 points at about 16,830.
Mr Hosokawa also said that Japan's past economic stimulus measures,
including a growth-oriented budget for the current fiscal year ending March
31 1994, were certain to promote economic recovery.
Last week, Mr Kazuo Aichi, in charge of policy for the Japan Renewal party,
the coalition partner responsible for economic policy, said the seven-party
coalition had agreed on the need to take some action to boost the economy
around December 7.
But the package began to look increasingly unlikely yesterday when plans hit
delays due to the coalition's hectic schedule. Mr Hiroshi Kumagai, minister
for international trade and industry, said on Japanese television that the
government was discussing no such plans and that it must now give top
priority to the supplementary budget required to finance part of the
Y6,150bn (Pounds 38.7bn) pump-priming package launched in September.
