<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Caldera nears poll victory in Caracas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A 77-year-old former head of state, Mr Rafael Caldera, yesterday proclaimed
his victory in Venezuela's presidential elections before thousands of
supporters as unofficial exit polls gave him a significant lead over his
rivals.
Mr Caldera, the pre-election favourite and candidate of a group of 17
parties, had secured between 30 and 35 per cent of the vote, according to
television exit polls. His margin of advantage over his three rivals
jostling for second place strongly suggested he would emerge as victor in
the official count.
Mr Claudio Fermn of the Democratic Action party, Mr Oswaldo Alvarez Paz of
the Christian Democrat Copei party, and Mr Andres Velasquez of the left-wing
Radical Cause party polled support in the low 20s per cent, according to
most exit polls.
Venezuelans also turned out in greater numbers than expected in the
elections for a new president, Congress and 22 state assemblies. Estimates
before the vote suggested as many as 35 to 40 per cent of voters would
abstain.
As the polling stations closed, there was no evidence of any disturbances
that would disrupt the elections.
The military said it uncovered last week a plot to derail the elections
involving active and retired officers in the armed forces and civilians.
If the results are confirmed, Mr Caldera will be 78 by the time he is
scheduled to take office, February 2. He broke away this year from Copei,
the party he helped found in 1946, to stand independently in the election.
President from 1969-74, he first stood in presidential elections in 1947. He
has vowed to reverse aspects of the economic reform programme introduced by
the administration of President Carlos Andres Perez, who was ousted this
year to allow his trial on corruption charges.
</TEXT>
