<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Spending plans by Commission upset ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday approved spending of nearly Ecu124bn
(Pounds 165bn) on public works programmes over the next six years, including
a new plan to float 'Brussels bonds' to help to finance the projects.
Mr Jacques Delors, Commission president, will present the plans to the
European summit on Friday, as part of his White Paper on employment and
growth, despite reservations among European finance ministers who were
meeting in Brussels last night.
Several ministers complained that Mr Delors had failed to produce a copy of
the White Paper; German officials expressed opposition to the notion of new
public borrowing to support infrastructure spending. 'It goes against our
policy of budgetary restraint,' said one Bonn official.
But Mr Edmond Alphandery, French finance minister, offered support for the
idea of additional finance to cover big road, rail, telecommunications and
environmental projects.
It remained unclear how finance ministers intend to integrate Mr Delors's
own non-binding White Paper with the legally binding but diluted version of
the macro-economic guidelines for the European Union, which were being
debated last night.
One official spoke of a 'power struggle' between the Commission and the
finance ministers who tend to look more to national rather than to
pan-European interests.
The Commission said yesterday that only Ecu7bn of the proposed annual
spending of Ecu20.6bn was new money. The rest has already been earmarked in
the budgetary guidelines approved last December at the European summit in
Edinburgh or through the European Investment Bank.
The Commission has identified trans-European network projects costing about
Ecu135bn. Officials believe these would improve European competitiveness by
strengthening the single market, but fear they could be delayed because
private banks and governments could object to the cost.
At the special session of the Commission yesterday, some members were said
to have criticised selective aspects of the White Paper which calls for
reforms in the labour market to make it easier to hire people, an effective
freeze on wages, and budget discipline.
