<HEADLINE>
FT  06 DEC 93 / Volvo chief denies he betrayed Gyllenhammar over merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GOTHENBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Soren Gyll, the chief executive of Volvo, yesterday denied he betrayed Mr
Pehr Gyllenhammar, who last week resigned as Volvo's chairman after Mr Gyll
led a management revolt against plans for a merger with Renault of France.
Mr Gyll in an interview with the Financial Times said: 'This is the worst
decision I have ever been involved in. It is a serious one, of course, but I
was prepared to take all the responsibility.'
The days leading up to Thursday's Volvo board meeting were fraught. Mr Gyll
decided a week ago that shareholder pressure meant the controversial merger
with Renault was unlikely to succeed.
But the crucial meeting was on Tuesday night when senior managers gathered
at Mr Gyll's home. After two hours of discussion the managers from Volvo's
car and truck divisions agreed the merger should not proceed.
The following day 25 managers signed a letter asking Mr Gyll to recommend
the board drop the merger plan. That day when Mr Gyllenhammar returned from
the US, Mr Gyll met him in private. He told him that the senior management
opposed the deal, which he believed was unlikely to be approved by
shareholders on December 7.
The following morning Mr Gyll warned his wife: 'This could be my last board
meeting.'
'I didn't know when I went into the board meeting what the outcome would
be,' he explained. 'They could have fired me. I could have been shooting
myself in the head.'
Mr Gyll reiterated his desire to continue a three-year old alliance with
Renault, saying joint projects could still be constructed on a 50-50 basis.
He said he would be talking with Mr Louis Schweitzer, the Renault chief
executive, as early as last night, although he acknowledged time was needed
for the two sides 'to cool down'.
How the French press saw the merger failure, Page 4
Gyll interview, Page 17
